<DOC><DOCNO> AP891127-0191 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 2215EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Rightists     11-27 0283</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Germany-Rightists,0292</SECOND><HEAD>Rightist Republicans Urge Reunited Germany</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   West Germany's ultraright-wingRepublican Party released on Monday a campaign platform calling fora reunited Germany that would include territory lost in World WarII.   Party chief Franz Schoenhuber, a former Waffen SS trooper,announced the platform for next year's elections and said theRepublicans have set up organizations in ``several locations'' inEast Germany.   He has made similar claims in the past. They were stronglydenied by East German communist authorities who say the RepublicanParty is neo-Nazi.   East Germany's official ADN news agency said Monday thatRepublican leaflets have appeared in the country.   ``Since the opening of the borders to the West, a rise inactivities of neo-Nazi groups in the direction of (East Germany)can be noticed,'' ADN said.   It said security officials will continue to fight all fascist,neo-Nazi and racist tendencies.   The Republicans' platform for the December 1990 federalelections in West Germany calls for a confederation between the twoGerman states as a first step. It said free and secret electionswould follow to choose leaders of a unified German government basedin Berlin.   It says East Germany must get out of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pactand West Germany must leave the North Atlantic Treaty Organizationto permit ``a bloc-free, reunited Germany.''   The 55-page program includes a map showing a united Germany andincluding former German territories in Poland and the Soviet Unionthat were lost with the defeat of Nazi Germany.   Schoenhuber said the lands legally belong to Germany until apeace treaty is signed.   He claimed the party has ``tripled in membership to 25,000''during the past year.</TEXT></DOC>